comments.body:
```suggestion
    if (auto* pindex{chain.Next(pindex_prev)}) {
```

PR description doesn't explain what `chain.Next` or `CChain::Contains` do in case of `chain.Tip()` or how we can test this manually or automatically.
It could also mention https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/blob/b58eebf1520f503bd4c7c5693546a6859064ce51/src/index/base.cpp#L220-L221 as an existing explanation.

There's also no problem description, where is this code used, what are we looking at (to help reviewers and to prove you understood the change), what we're trying to solve exactly (`CChain::FindFork` meant for reorgs, it's walking the ancestor chain which is more expensive for tip than it needs to be).

@optout21's framing is best: "a slight optimization -- early exit handling of a special case" 

It's also stating: "handles a specific case in a wrong way" which is too strong: the behavior was correct, just hacky - it still returned `nullptr`, it's just a bit unorthodox to do it via out of bounds in https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/blob/1c2f164d348675382338bd60ea49a4105daa6fef/src/chain.h#L405-L406.

Instead of explaining with comments, it would be even simpler to explain via a new test, something like:
```patch
diff --git a/src/test/chain_tests.cpp b/src/test/chain_tests.cpp
--- a/src/test/chain_tests.cpp	(revision b58eebf1520f503bd4c7c5693546a6859064ce51)
+++ b/src/test/chain_tests.cpp	(date 1770123142310)
@@ -82,4 +82,21 @@
     }
 }
 
+BOOST_AUTO_TEST_CASE(cchain_contains_next_test)
+{
+    CBlockIndex block0, block1;
+    block0.nHeight = 0;
+    block1.nHeight = 1;
+    block1.pprev = &block0;
+
+    CChain chain;
+    chain.SetTip(block1);
+
+    BOOST_CHECK(chain.Contains(&block0));
+    BOOST_CHECK_EQUAL(chain.Next(&block0), &block1);
+
+    BOOST_CHECK(chain.Contains(&block1));
+    BOOST_CHECK_EQUAL(chain.Next(&block1), nullptr);  // Next(Tip) == nullptr
+}
+
 BOOST_AUTO_TEST_SUITE_END()

```

